<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1>ESSUM28250 - Approval of SIPs: Establishing a plan</h1>
<p>The SIP must be established by a company before it can be approved by HM Revenue and Customs; documentary evidence of this will need to be produced prior to the approval of any SIP.  This means the plan must have come into existence from a legal point of view. </p>
<p>Companies should take their own legal advice on how a SIP should be set up. Establishment is generally by execution of the deed of trust following a resolution of the company's shareholders in general meeting to adopt the plan rules. In some cases directors may have powers to adopt the rules of a SIP under the company's Articles of Association. Scheme advisers should not advise on the powers of directors, which are a matter of company law.</p>
<p>The relevant Companies Act requirements on passing resolutions are at Section 30(1) Companies Act 2006.  The procedures by which private companies must pass resolutions can be found at sections 288 &amp; 289 Companies Act 2006.  </p>
<h3>The plan</h3>
<p>Paragraph 81(2) gives the HMRC power to request "such particulars" and "such evidence" to be submitted in writing as is required to consider an application for approval.  In practice this means requesting those documents which are considered to form part of the plan as a whole.</p>
<p>In considering what forms part of a plan, it is necessary to decide from the evidence in each case what is and is not relevant.  Scheme advisers should consider the following to be part of the SIP:</p>
<ul>
<li>the trust deed, and the plan rules and the ancillary documents to be used in operating them</li>
<li>the provisions in the company's Articles of Association which regulate the shares and therefore affect the operation of the SIP</li>
<li>the terms of any shareholders agreements to which shares acquired under the SIP may be subject</li>
<li>any arrangements made between the SIP administrator (or the company) and the participants</li>
<li>invitation documents prepared in conjunction with the trustee or administrator</li>
</ul>
<p>Care should be taken where a SIP submitted for approval has schedules or another scheme annexed to it which do not form part of the SIP for which approval is being sought. Approval can only be given to a particular plan, or an identifiable part of an overall plan, which satisfies the relevant requirements of Schedule 2. If approval is being given only to an identifiable part of an overall plan, this should be made clear in the approval letter.</p>
<h3>The company</h3>
<p>Paragraph 2(2) refers to “the company" as the company which established the plan and it is that company which must apply for approval of the SIP even if the shares to be used are those of another company. </p>
<h3>Group plans</h3>
<p>SIPs can be extended to include subsidiary companies of “the company” if those companies are under the control (within the meaning of Section 719 ITEPA 2003) of the company which established the plan. These are known as “group plans”. There is no statutory authority for extending a scheme to other companies. The company and nominated participating subsidiaries are referred to as “constituent companies” (paragraph 4(3)).</p>
<p>A SIP which is established by a company which is itself a subsidiary company cannot include as constituent companies its own parent company or fellow subsidiaries.</p>
<p>A list of the constituent companies should be submitted with the application for approval, but subsequent additions or withdrawals are not required to be notified to ESSU. A company’s introduction as a constituent company in a group plan cannot be backdated to a time before it was formally admitted in accordance with the Deed and rules of the SIP.</p>
<p> “Control” has the meaning given in section 719 ITEPA 2003 and will normally include companies in which the company owns more than 50% of the shares.  Scheme advisers may accept SIPs which also define subsidiary companies by reference to Section 1159 of the Companies Act 2006.</p>
